summary: Creating my own post because there’s been a whole bunch of negative ones on my feed, getting more and more aggressive and...
body:
Creating my own post because there’s been a whole bunch of negative ones on my feed, getting more and more aggressive and negative as it goes on.

I like The Last Jedi. It brought new material in, which was a necessary step for the next trilogy to get moving (especially since TFA’s storyline played it safe and emulated ANH’s plotline to draw audiences in. Going somewhere new with a known and beloved franchise is hard, and honestly I think TLJ would not have improved if it tried to emulate TESB in a similar fashion).

It’s not a bad movie, and it’s certainly not as bad as y’all make it out to be (it didn’t “ruin the franchise”; you’re all going to see the next one, don’t even play). Not every Star Wars movie is going to be a cinematic milestone like The Empire Strikes Back, and TLJ is definitely not the worst in the lineup.

The negativity around TLJ really needs to stop, too. Some of y’all take SW way too seriously, and then actually say/do shitty things to each other, to actors, to writers, to directors, etc. to “”””punish them”””” for making something you didn’t personally agree with, and, fellas, it’s just a movie.

It’s just a movie.

tags: this was supposed to be funny
body:
Star Wars and Tattoos

I’ve seen a recent influx of a certain Jedi General with tattoos (Obi-Wan, duh) and I’ve been thinking - wouldn’t it be hilarious if he’s actually tatted up?

Like, everyone expects Anakin to be, but no? Everyone’s already surprised he’s shredded to begin with - they fail to miss the tattoo of the Republic alliance, the birth and death dates of Qui-Gon Ginn, the outline of his first ship, maybe a Mandalorian lily or flower? There’s even a quote from a philosopher (Shakespeare) “Love all, trust few, do wrong to none.”

Anakin’s mouth drops when he finally registers what he’s seeing. “How - when - why?”

Obi-Wan twirls his lightsaber around and settles into the Sorseu opening stance. “I had an adventurous youth. Ready on three?”

Nobody does notice the little semi-colan etched onto his wrist, covering a few self-harm cuts. If they do notice, they keep quiet. Kix does during the battle of Point Rain, and sits by Obi-Wan while he recovers, refusing to leave his side until all is well. (He has one too. Many of his brothers do.)

When the twins are born, he has their birthdates etched into his skin, below the dates marking Satine’s life.

He is relieved he never has to etch their deaths onto his skin.
